{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_calhoun_ver01/data/sn83016244/00513689925/1958042301/0579.xml":{"full_text":"West, Florida, has the\nmost equable climate In the\ncountry, with an average\nrange of only 14* Fahrenheit\nVOL. LXXIX No. 97\nNavy Civilian, Military Payroll $32,250,000 Here\nNavy Buys 8375,000 Annually From\nKey West Businessmen; May Increase\nWater Rates Are\nRaised 25% By\n\nAqueduct Body\nBondholders\nWanted Price\nProtection\nk r.-v\nFlorida Keys Aqueduct\nCommission said today that\nthe price of water has been\nraised 25 cents on the dol\nlar to a new rate of |1.25\nper 1,000 gallons.\nErnest Ramsey, aqueduct\ncommission manager, said\nthe rate increase was voted\nby the commission Monday\nat the same meeting at\nwhich a 13,800,000 bond\nissue was sold to finance\nnew pumping facilities and\nwater mains.\nThe new* of the rate increase\nfallowed a news release by Aque\nduct Commissioner Louis M. J.\nEisner Tuesday on the sal* of\nth* bonds, which the aqueduct\ncommission has been trying to\nmarket far more than two years.\n\u201cTwo main things were respon\nsible for the rate increase,\" Ram-\nHy said.\n\"Flrat af all, people who *f\nferod to buy A* bend* lr*\nHaupt and Cwnpany *f How\nY*rir City s*k*d that we\nral** our rate* to 1118 pw U\n881 gallon*, l***t, to give\nthem more **corify far th*\nm*n*y th*y wer* lending u*.\nTh*** *r* r*v*nu* bend*;\nHwy don't bind th* taxpayer* *f\nMenre* C*unty In *ny w*y, and\ncan *nly be paid off through\nreceipt* from water bill*.\n\"Socendty.\" mW \"t**\nNavy ho* r*l*od It* price* on\nthe water it *oll* u*.\u201c\nThe aqueduct commi*\u00bbion ab\nsorbed an 11 cents per 1,000\ngallons price increase by the Na\nvy last summer without raising its\nrate*. The Navy, faced with high\ner operating costs on it* pipeline,\njumped the price of water it \u00abeUs\n\u201cwholesale\u201d to the aqueduct com\nmission from about 39 cents per\n1,000 gallons to 50 cents in July,\n1957.\nThis July, Ramsey said, the\nprice will go' to 55 cents, meaning\nanother nickel added to the wa\nter rates to satisfy bond buyers\nand give the aqueduct commis\naion a safe margin of money to\nmaintain water main* and replace\nold ones as they wear out.\nThe new bond issue, due to\nbe paid off between now and 1979,\nwill pay for new pumping sta\ntions at Cross, Long and Ramrod\nKey, and an extra pump at Flori\nda City. The new pumps will push\nsome 20 to 30 per cent more water\n(Continued On Page Four)\nParole Violator\nSurrenders Here\nA 25 year -old man who\n*aid he was a Connecticut parole\nviolator surrendered to the sher\niff\u2019s office here last night.\nLt Rene Raiole identified the\nman as Adolph Salvati of Mid\ndleton, Conn. He told officers he\nhad been heading shrimp here\nand that he \u201cwas tired of run\nning.\u201d Lt. Raiole notified Con\nnecticut authorities.\nK\n\nI\n71\nINJURED ITBI FLBJACKS RBSCUBD-Jam** And*r**n, feurth\nman up from l*ff, I* *W*d dawn *xt*n*lan ladder from 135-foat\nwafer tawwr after he auffarad injuries when knocked to bottom of\nhwido of tank. Anatfwr worker, removed ahoed ef Anderson,\nwe* James Golden, who fell Inside tank, carrying Anderson with\nhim to tank bottom. Golden suffered broken arm and fractured\npelvis. Anderson escaped with Internal Injuries.\u2014AP Wirephoto.\n9\n1\nIke Says Recession\nHas Flattened Out\nBy MARVIN L. ARROWSMITH\nWASHINGTON (A- President\nEisenhower Mid today he believes\nthe business recession has been\nflattening out for tome time and\nthat Americans should guard\nagainst becoming hysterical about\nthe slump.\nEisenhower told a news confer\nence he is not attempting to be\nPollyannaish about the recession\nand contend that everything is\nlovely.\nThere still is a lot of agonizing\nreappraisal going on in the admin\nistration about how to deal with\nthe slump, Eisenhower continued.\nBut, the President said, he\nwants to speak out once more\nagainst any hasty action on a tax\ncut, and he made it clear no re\nquest to Congress for a reduction\nis imminent.\nIt was at this point that Eisen\nhower said be believes the reces\nsion has been flattening out for\nsome time, and added that we\nshould not get hysterical about the\nsituation.\nQuestioned about criticism by\nDemocratic leaders that the ad\nministration hasn\u2019t been moving\nfast enough against the recession\nand has not displayed boldness\nand courage, Eisenhower replied\nthA it is well enough to talk about\nboldness and courage once you\nhave a plan developed for dealing\nwith the situation.\nBut he said the administration\nTHE SOUTHERNMOST NEWSPAPEV/bMKBy\nstill is studying the picture to\nmake sure it will be right in any\nanti-recession move.\nWe are just trying to be right,\nEisenhower repeated.\nHe said that in hi* view the ad\nmioistration has made quite an\nimpressive record since last Sep\ntember in dealing with the reces\nsion.\nThis was Eisenhower\u2019* fifth\nnews conference in as \u2019many\nweeks. Not since 1954, when the\nPresident met with newsmen eight\nweeks in a row, has there been\nsuch an unbroken atring of con\nferences.\nEisenhower's mood ranged be\ntween joviality and outright irrita\ntion.\nAside from the recession, he\ndealt with there other topics:\nDEFENSE Eisenhower'\nsnapped that a questioner might\njust as well say that Congress is\nnuts and Wants to abolish the De\nfense Department, as to put any\nstock in contention* in Congress\nthat the administration\u2019s Pentagon\nreorganization program could lead\nto a one man, personalized mili\ntary force\u2014a kind of dictatorship.\nObviously Irritated, Eisenhower\nasked Sarah McClendon, who rep\nresent* Texas newspapers, wheth\ner she had read the law before\nbringing up that matter to him.\nMi** McClendon replied she had\n(Conticuad on Pag* Four)\nKRY WMT, FLORIDA, WBDNBBDAY, APRIL 13, ImF\nBuilding\nSuppliers\nGet $lOO,OOO\nThe U. 8* Navy buys\nsome 1375,000 worth of\neverything from \u201chatchets\nto hammer-handlM\u201d from\nKey West .businesses each\nyear, Rear Admiral F. D.\nMcCorkle, Naval Base com*\nmander, said this week.\n\u201cAnd conceivably,\u201d the\nAdmiral said, \u201cthis amount\nwill be increased as com\nmerce and industry, with\nresultant diversified in\nventories, are developed in\nKey West\u201d\nThe Admiral\u2019* letter, with, m\naccompanying booklet on \"Sup\nplying Your Nivy,\u201d rent The Ci\ntizen to the Naval Bate purchas\ning department for extra infor\nmation which showed that the buy\ning done here covers an extreme,\nly wide raqge of items.\nOne of the biggest categories\nis building supplies, such as lum\nber, floor cowring, light fixtures,\nplumbing fixtures concrete block\nsend, sod, soil, shingles sod other\nitems. This runs to roughly 8100,-\n000 t year.\nAnother big category, the No\nvy says, is auto parts, tome\n825,088 worth of these ore\nbought hero each year, along\nwith perhaps 325,000 worth of\npaints, rust preventative* and\nether chemical*.\nRefrigeration, air conditioning\nsupplies, office supplies, hard\nware (which covers about 8,000\nitems ranging, literally, from\n\"hatchets to hammer handles\")\nand some food supplies.\nThe Navy, like y>e rest of mili\ntary installations across the na\ntion, gets the bulk of its food\nsupplies shipped to it from cen\ntral supply depots.\nFresh foods generally are\nbought by the government in\ngiant lots and shipped here from\nColumbia, South Carolina or Jack-\nsonville, Fla., military supply cen\nters. Non perishable items like 1\ncanned goods are bought and\nstored at .the Atlanta General\nDepot, U, S. Army, in Atlanta,\nGa., where they\u2019re shipped to all 1\nmilitary installations\u2014Army, Navy,\n(Continued on Pago Four) 1\nCounty Taxpayers\nTo Regain $19,000\nTALLAHASSEE Uri-The Florida\nSupreme Court today refused with\nout comment to reconsider its rul\ning banning collection of doubled\nMonroe County Tax Collector\u2019s\noffice said today this decition\nwould mean refunds of some 319,.\n000 for county taxpayers. The of\nfice had collected 338,800 Under\nthe new rate schedule and sent\nthe money on to Tallahassee.\nAll money raised by intangi\nbles taxes goes into the state\ntreasury. None is kept by counties\nor cities.\nintangible personal property tax\nes for 1957.\nThe decision win cost the state\nsix million dollars.\nA rehearing had been asked by\nAtty. Gen. Richard Ervin on be\nhalf of State Comptroller Ray E.\nGreen.\nIntangible taxes are collected on\ncash in the bank, stocks and bonds\nheld by the taxpayer as of Jan. 1.\nHie 1957 Legislature raised the\ntax on bank deposits from one\ntwentieth to one-tenth mill and on\nstocks and bonds from one to two\nmills.\nThe court\u2019l original decision\nheld that the new rate could not\nbe applied on 1957 holdings be\ncause retroactivity was not spe\ncifically spelled out in the act.\nUtility Board Silent On City\nRequest To Cut Rates Here\n4\nSi\nf Tl\n7 I/ i\nIf 4\n1I J 1\ni i Ww wS\nk X K\nB ML J \u25a0gLIQH\nUS W.\n\"HAPPY BIRTHDAY, KIWANIS\u201d-S\u00abriior past president William V. Albury cut the birthday cake\n*la*t night a* Key West Kiwanis Club marked it* 10th anniversary. Standing, left to right, are char\nter member Harry Mitchell; Dr. Harvey Cohn of Upper Koya Kiwanis Club, guest speaker; current\nKey West Kiwanis president Bill Warner; Albury; and charter member* Glynn Archer and Ralph\nFaralge. Ira Albury, secretary since the club was founded 10 years ago, is 111 and couldn't attend\nthe special program.\u2014Citizen Staff Photo, Rod Birkett.\nKiwanians Celebrate 10 Years\nOf Progress In Island City\nWith a wish for \u201c10 more' years\nof progress,\u201d senior past president\nWilliam V. Albury blew out the\ncandles on Key West Kiwanis\nClub\u2019s birthday cake at a special\n\u201cLadies Night\u201d program Tues\nday.\nSome 40 Kiwanians, wives and\nguests crowded into Logon\u2019s din-\ning room for the club\u2019s 10th an-\nniversary celebration dinner, pia\nno selections by two Convent of\nFLOWN TO HOSPITAL\u2014Dr. Horman K. Moore hurries aboard a\nNavy plane here today, holding his 3-yoar-old son, Richard, for a\nquick trip to Miami and Variety Children's Hospital. Tests on\nthe bey here proved Inconclusive but persons suffering from polio\nusually ore token from hero to the tamo hospital. On April 1 a\nnurse In Dr. Moore'* office was stricken with bulbar polio.\u2014Offi\ncial U.S. Navy Photo.\nMary Immaculate students and a\ntalk by Dr. Harvey W. Cohn, pre\nsident of the Upper Keys Kiwanis\nClub.\nDr. Cohn, representing Kiwanis\nlieutenant governor Harry Har\nris, reminded th^ club that it\u2019a\none of more than 3,700 Kiwanis\nclubs in the United States, Ca\nnada, Alaska and Hawaii with\nsome 225,000 members.\n\"It's a club,\u201d ho said, \"thit\ncould help control to a groat ex\ntent just how wo wish the Keys\nto bo in the next few year* a*\nthey develop.\u201d\nDr. Cohn presented 10 year\nperfect attendance pin* to Joe\nBoza (absent Tuesday), and Al\nbury; a nine year pin for Dr.\nH./C. Campbell, also away, to\nMrs. Campbell; eight year pins\nto Glynn Archer and Ralph Far\naldo and seven year pins to Har\nry Mitchell and Kent Mack.\nPat Kelly, club president Bill\nWarner and Colonel Holbrook got\nsix year pin*; Newt Ketching*\nand Lefty Reagan, the latter ab\nsent, five year pin* and four\nyear pins to Skippy Rueda, miu\ning Tuesn^y; Manuel Lopez and\nGaley Sweeting.\nKiwanians and wive* welcom\ned excellently done piano \u2022el\nection* by the Convent students,\nGeorgia Lee Garcia who played\n\u201cPony Race\u201d and Vivian Gar\ning, \u2018Prelude in G Minor.\u201d\nOtto Busot and Richard Padron,\nvisiting members of the Kiwan\nis sponsored Key West High\nSchool Key Club, presented the\n\u201ctraveling key\u201d to Sweeting,\nwho\u2019ll return it *t a visit to the\nboys\u2019 meeting. The group sang\ntwo \u201cHappy Birthdays\u201d one to\nthe club itself and another to\nKelly.\nWatching Albury cut the an\nni.v*r**ry c*k* Tuesday w*r*\nvisiting Klwanian Dr. Tad Light\nof Dayton, Ohio; Mr. and Mr*.\nJore Blanco Jr., guest* of Ki\nwanian Max Labrad*; Mr. and\nMrs. Ralph Fara Ma, Mr. and\nMr*. Holbrook, Mr, and Mr*.\nTony Tarracino, Mr. and Mr\nMitchell, Mr t and Mr*. Albury,\nTony Torrocino, Mr. and Mrt.\nMitchell, Mr.and Mr*. Albury,\nMr. and Mra. Warner and Mr.\nand Mr*. Lopez.\nX\nOther couples present were the\nGlynn Archers, the Retchings, the\nKent Macks, the Bill Daniels and\nand the Warners, with Pat Kelly,\nJeff Brodhead, Galey Sweeting\nand Charli* Child* also present.\nWeatKer Summary\nFair to partly cloudy this after\nnoon and tonight. Chance of\nshowers Thursday. Low tonight\nabout 78. High Thursday 85. To\nmarrow\u2019s tides, High 5:58 a. m.,\n8:54 p. m. Low, 10:07 a, m., 11:48\np. m.\nPRICB FIVi CBNTI\nLaw Allows City\nElectric To Set\n\nIts Own Rates\nKey West Utility Board\nmembers and City Electric x\nSystem manager kept silent\ntoday In the wake of a city\ncommission move to cut the\nprice of electricity supplied\nto local homes and busi\nnesses.\nThe city commissioners\nTuesday night indicated\nthey were embarking on a\n\u201cget tough\u201d policy with the\nelectric system, managed\nby the utility board.\nCommissioner Joo Fernandez\nhad asked the city attorney to\ndraw up an ordinance repealing\na former commission ordinance\nwhich approved the \u2019fluctuating\nratiK' that ties electric bi hi Ja\nthe rising and falling cost of fu\u00abL\noil. Wk\nOther commissioner* Indicat\ned they backed Mayor Dolle\nCobo and Commissioner BUI\nChappell who are also mem\nber* of the five man utility\nboard In their attempt* to\ngot the lloctrlc System to fur\nnish free power to the city gov\nernment. The municipal light\nbill we* 348,0 N last year.\nThe other three member* of th*\nutility board are Ben Adams; Hor\nace O\u2019Bryant, also county school\nsuperintendent; and Ernest Ram\nsey, also aqueduct commission\nmanager. O'Bryant is chairman.\nMerville E. Rosam, electric sys\ntem manager, said he\u2019d rather not\ncomment on the city commis\nsion\u2019s discussion, feeling any com\nment involved utility board policy\nand should'come from the board.\nRamsey declined to comment\nas an individual member, feeling\na statement should come from\nthe full board or at last have\n1 O\u2019Bryant\u2019s approval, since he is\nthe chairm sn.\nO'Bryant was out of town tills\nmorning, however. Adams could\nI not be reached for comment.\nA check of the state law which\nsets up the utility board, how-\n(Continued on Page Four)\nWoman Killed,\nMan Hurt In\nAuto Wreck\nA woman was killed and a man\nseriously injured at 4 a. m. today\nwhen their car ran off the high\nway 114 miles south of the Dade\nMonroe County line.\nFlorida Highway Patrol troop\ner Robert Young reported that\nLillian May Ewart, 38, of HaUen\ndale was killed and Allen Catz,\n37, of Miami Beach was serious\nly injured.\nYeung said Catz was driving\na 1954 Ford convertible south\non U. S. 1 when th* car ran\noff the right side of the high\nway, then back acres* to the\nleft side. The convertible jump\ned the water lino and then over\nturned.\nCatz was taken to the James\nArcher Smith Hospital at Home\nstead where he was reported\nsuffering from a fractured skull\nand a fractured right arm.\nThe death was Monroe County\u2019s\nfifth traffic fatality this year. Up\nto this date last year, four per\nsons bad died in traffic accidents\nin this county.","height":"29098","width":"20636"}}
